##Variable            ##Description

#ID                    #ID Number of Customers         

#Warehouse Block       #Company`s Warehouses such as A,B,C,D,F

#Mode of shipment      #The way the company ships the products (Ship, Flight, Road)

#Customer care calls   #The number of calls made from customers for inquiry of the shipment

#Customer ratings      #The rating of the customers for the service of the company based on prior purchases 1(the lowest) to 5(the highest)

#Cost of the product   #Cost of the product in US dollars

#Prior purchases       #The number of prior purchases from each customer

#Product importance    #The importance of the purchased product specified by company (such as low, medium, high)

#Gender                #Male or female

#Discount offered      #Discount offered on that specific purchased product

#Weight in gms         #The weight of the product in grams

#Reached on time       #The target variable, 1 indicates that the product has NOT reached on time and 0 otherwise

The variable ID will not be that much important for my project so I will drop this column out. I suppose that all warehouses have similar on-time delivery rates so Warehouse Block might not contribute much to the predictive power of my model. Mode of shipment could be a crucial variable as different shipping methods may have varying delivery times resulting in more on - time deliveries. I converted it into a factor variable to be able to make calculations later on. The Customer Care Calls could indicate customer dissatisfaction or issues with the delivery process. Higher number might correlate with delays.

Higher product costs might be associated with extra or higher premium services, potentially influencing on-time delivery, so the Cost of the product variable might help to explore this relationship. Prior purchases tells how many times that specific customer has made a purchase. Customers with a history of prior purchases might have different experiences with the delivery process. It could be a relevant predictor for the models which will be built later on.

The importance of the product purchased by the customer, which is shown by the Product importance, column might influence the level of care and attention given during shipping. Initially, the variable was identified as a character type. I converted the Product Importance variable to an ordered factor to represent the ordinal nature of the categories (low, medium, high).

I think that the sex of the customers might not necessarily influence on-time delivery. The Gender variable will not be much important. The impact of discounts on delivery time might be a crucial factor for the prediction. This is showed by Discount offered column.

When we talk about the weight of the purchased products it is important to know that heavier products might require more time for processing and shipping, potentially impacting the delivery time. This will be explored in the Weight in gms column. Reached on time is the target binary variable which indicates if the product reached on time or not

Data manipulation

Firstly, I checked for missing values and duplicates. Fortunately, no missing values were found and there were no duplicate rows. Then I dropped out 2 irrelevant columns in order to make my work easier and more efficient while doing calculations and building the models.

By looking at the structure of the data I distinguished that 3 variables needed to be converted into factors in order to be able to make calculations.

To gain a deeper understanding of the dataset, I employed the summary function. I observed that the most common mode of shipment was Ship with a significant lead over Flight and Road. This information is crucial for understanding the distribution of shipping methods within dataset. The summary statistics showed that the highest product cost was 310 $ , while the lowest cost was recorded at 96 $ . This broad range in product costs is noteworthy and will be further explored in the analyses. It revealed interesting insights into the distribution of Product_importance. While the highest level of product importance high was assigned to 948 products, the other two levels low and medium had a higher frequency

Logistic Regression

I started with the Logistic Regression model by using the R base function glm.

Then, I saw the vectors by looking at the coefficients. I found the most influential variables which resulted to be the Product importance. This variable has the largest positive coefficient, suggesting that higher levels of product importance increase the likelihood of the product not reaching on time. Discount offered also plays a crucial role. It showed that the products with higher discount rates have a higher probability to not reach on time. Another influential variable was Prior purchases. High numbers of prior purchases decreases the probability of the delivery not reaching on time, emphasizing the impact of customer loyalty. Variables like Weight did not show significant influence on arrival time.

Exploring the predicted class probabilities p2 under fitted values, I applied a decision rule by putting a condition where all the class probabilities greater than 0.5 would receive a 1 binary value. Otherwise, a 0 will be assigned. The accuracy of the model (the share of correct class predictions) is 64 %

#Estimate the logistic model
model_logit <-glm(Reached_on_Time ~ Mode_of_Shipment + Customer_care_calls + Customer_rating + Cost_of_the_Product + Prior_purchases + Product_importance + Gender + Discount_offered + Weight_in_gms, data=my_data, family = "binomial")

Decision Trees

I initiated my analysis by constructing a decision tree using the rpart function. The resulting tree structure was visualized using the prp function.

Subsequently, I aimed to simplify the tree model through pruning.

I evaluated the accuracy of the decision tree by comparing its predictions to the actual values of Reached_on_Time where I got a 68.4 % accuracy.

To further optimize the decision tree model, I conducted an exploration of hyperparameters. I put different values for the minimum observations min_obs, maximum depth max_depth, and complexity parameter cp_val and ran a grid search. The grid search explored different combinations of the hyperparameters to find the set that would maximize the accuracy. For each combination of hyperparameters, I built decision tree models, calculated their accuracy, and stored the results in a structured format. The results were visualized in a 3D scatter plot, where the color scale indicated the model accuracy across different parameter settings. This visualization identified a parameter region with better model performance. From the hyperparameter exploration, I selected the combination of hyperparameters that yielded the highest accuracy. This optimal parameter set was then used to construct a final decision tree model (model_tree_3). The mean accuracy of this models predictions was calculated and found to be 70 %

# Model the tree
model_tree <- rpart(data=my_data, formula = Reached_on_Time ~ Mode_of_Shipment + Customer_care_calls + Customer_rating + Cost_of_the_Product + Prior_purchases + Product_importance + Discount_offered + Weight_in_gms, method="class")
prp(model_tree)


plotcp(model_tree)


# Determine the minimum complexity parameter (cp) for pruning
min_cp <- model_tree$cptable[which.min(model_tree$cptable[, "xerror"]), "CP"]
# Prune the decision tree model using the minimum cp
model_tree_2 <- prune(model_tree, cp = min_cp )
# Plot the pruned decision tree model
prp(model_tree_2)


mean(predict(model_tree, my_data, type = "class")==my_data$Reached_on_Time)
[1] 0.6841531
## Investigating hyperparameters
# Define the values for minimum observations, maximum depth, and complexity parameter (cp)
min_obs <- seq(from = 5, to = 50, by = 5)
max_depth <- c(1, 5, 10, 15)
cp_val <- c(0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1)

# Create an empty data frame to store the results
results <- data.frame()

# Iterate over the combinations of min_obs, max_depth, and cp_value
for (i in 1:length(min_obs)) {
  for (j in 1:length(max_depth)) {
    for (k in 1:length(cp_val)) {
      # Build a decision tree model with the specified parameters
      model <- rpart(data = my_data, formula = Reached_on_Time ~ Mode_of_Shipment + Customer_care_calls + Customer_rating + Cost_of_the_Product + Prior_purchases + Product_importance + Discount_offered + Weight_in_gms, 
                     method = "class",
                     cp = cp_val[k],
                     maxdepth = max_depth[j],
                     minbucket = min_obs[i])
      
      # Calculate the accuracy of the model predictions
      acc <- mean(predict(model, my_data, type = "class") == my_data$Reached_on_Time)
      
      # Store the accuracy and parameter values to the results data frame
      results <- rbind(results, c(acc, min_obs[i], max_depth[j], cp_val[k]))
    }
  }
}

# Set column names for the results data frame
colnames(results) <- c("accuracy", "min_obs", "max_depth", "cp")

# Create a 3D scatter plot using scatter3D
plot3D::scatter3D(x = results$min_obs, y = results$max_depth, z = results$cp,
                  theta = 30, phi = 10,
                  xlab = "Min Obs", ylab = "Max Depth", zlab = "CP",
                  ticktype = "detailed",
                  pch = 19,
                  cex.axis = 0.75, cex.lab = 0.75, expand = 0.75,
                  colvar = results$accuracy, col = viridis(100))




# Select the optimal parameter combination with the highest accuracy and store them
opt_params <- results[which.max(results$accuracy),]

# Build a decision tree model using the optimal parameters
model_tree_3 <- rpart(data=my_data, formula = Reached_on_Time ~ Mode_of_Shipment + Customer_care_calls + Customer_rating + Cost_of_the_Product + Prior_purchases + Product_importance + Discount_offered + Weight_in_gms, 
                      method = "class",
                      cp = opt_params$cp, 
                      maxdepth = opt_params$max_depth, 
                      minbucket = opt_params$min_obs)

# Calculate the mean accuracy of the model predictions
mean(predict(model_tree_3, my_data, type = "class") == my_data$Reached_on_Time)
[1] 0.7089735
# Plot the optimal decision tree
prp(model_tree_3, main = "Tree with optimal parameters")

Model Evaluation

Now, I built a confusion matrix to check how many observations I got correct and how many wrong. Firstly, I used the model of logistic regression as I explained earlier and the decision rules where the predicted probability of not reaching on time was greater than 0.5, the product was classified as not reaching on time ; otherwise, it was classified as reaching on time. Then, I created another confusion matrix. This time I evaluated the optimized decision tree.

We can see that the decision tree model did much better in terms of sensitivity with an accuracy of 83 % . This kind of model has predicted Product reaches on time pretty well. On the other side the logistic regression predicted the true negative values ( Specificity -> to not reach on time) a bit better. The accuracy was 68 % . We could tell, so far, that the tree has done a much better prediction in comparison with logistic regression.

After that, I wanted to increase the accuracy of the logistic regression. I looped through all thresholds from 0.01 to 0.99 and found the accuracy for each data point for each different threshold. After that, I stored the results in the data frame and plotted a graph that showed the relationship between thresholds and accuracy. I noticed that I could do better for the logistic regression by increasing the threshold a bit more. Lastly, I built another logistic regression. This time with the new threshold which would increase the accuracy that the graph showed. At the end the accuracy that I got was 65.5 %

Overall, if we compare the 2 models implemented in my project, we could tell that the tree model made a better prediction, with an accuracy of 70.9 % in comparison with the logistic regression where we got a 65.5 % accuracy at the end.

#Increasing the accuracy of logistic regression
thresholds <- seq(0.01, 0.99, by = 0.01)


threshold_results <- data.frame(Threshold = thresholds, Accuracy = numeric(length(thresholds)))

#Loop 
for (i in seq_along(thresholds)) {
  predictions <- ifelse(model_logit$fitted.values > thresholds[i], 1, 0)
  accuracy <- mean(predictions == my_data$Reached_on_Time)
  threshold_results$Accuracy[i] <- accuracy
}

#Storing the threshold that maximizes accuracy
optimal_threshold <- threshold_results$Threshold[which.max(threshold_results$Accuracy)]


#Thresholds vs accuracy plot
ggplot(threshold_results, aes(x = Threshold, y = Accuracy)) +
  geom_line(color = "cyan3") +
  labs(x = "Threshold", y = "Accuracy", title = "Threshold vs Accuracy") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = optimal_threshold, color = "coral") +
  xlim(0, 1)+
  theme_minimal()

Feature Engineering

At this part I wanted to apply Feature Engineering to my dataset. Firstly, I built a correlation matrix to show the correlation between the numeric variables. I distinguished a positive relationship of 0.32 for the Cost of the product and Customer care calls. In this case, I expect that as the price of the product increases, customers may require more customer assistance because they care more for their product. I found reasonable to create a new variable by multiplying these 2 variables and add a new column named Calls_cost. This new variable would capture the interaction between Cost of the product and Customer care calls. This means that the impact on my target variable would not be influenced only by the costs and number of customer care calls alone but also by their combined effect. After I created the new variable, I run the logistic model. This time I also included the new variable. By checking at the coefficients I noticed that the effect of Calls cost with the target variable was negative. This means that, an increase in this variable would decrease the probability of not reaching on time . At the end, the model was improved but not with a high increase.

ggcorrplot(corr = cor(my_data[, .(Customer_care_calls, Cost_of_the_Product, Prior_purchases, Discount_offered, Weight_in_gms, Reached_on_Time)]), 
           hc.order = TRUE,
